---
// About section — personal story and background.
---
<section id="about" class="py-24 px-4 bg-page">
  <div class="max-w-2xl mx-auto">
    <span class="reveal section-label" style="--reveal-delay: 0ms">About</span>
    <h2 class="reveal text-3xl md:text-4xl font-bold text-center mb-10 text-theme" style="--reveal-delay: 80ms">A bit about me</h2>
    <div class="space-y-5 text-muted text-base md:text-lg leading-relaxed">
      <p class="reveal" style="--reveal-delay: 160ms">
        I got into web development around 2014, mostly by pulling apart WordPress themes to see what
        broke. That trial-and-error time with HTML, CSS, and JavaScript stuck with me longer than any
        tutorial did.
      </p>
      <p class="reveal" style="--reveal-delay: 220ms">
        Since then I've worked with clients, startups, and a Shopify apps company — spending a lot of
        time at the intersection of front-end code and merchant support. A good chunk of that was
        diagnosing Shopify storefront issues: cart drawer conflicts, broken app embeds, checkout
        quirks, and the kind of bugs that only appear on one browser at one screen size.
      </p>
      <p class="reveal" style="--reveal-delay: 280ms">
        What I find genuinely interesting is the gap between "the error exists" and "the merchant
        understands what happened and can move forward." That translation layer from stack trace to
        clear next step is something I've gotten a lot of practice at.
      </p>
      <p class="reveal" style="--reveal-delay: 340ms">
        Outside of client work, I'm building out a set of resources: debugging checklists, reusable
        snippets, and practical guides aimed at the exact problems I've seen come up repeatedly in
        Shopify and front-end work.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>